With Republicans in firm control of the Supreme Court in 2018, the high court decided not to decide Gill, leaving Wisconsin’s gerrymander in place.
All of which is a long way of saying that the outcomes in Rucho v. Common Cause and Lamone v. Benisek, two partisan gerrymandering cases that the Supreme Court will hear next Tuesday, are practically preordained.
The court’s roleEven before Kavanaugh’s arrival, the Supreme Court’s Republican majority cut deep into America’s democratic norms.
Ordinarily, when the Supreme Court takes up monumental cases like Rucho and Benisek, my job is to lay out the legal issues in those cases and offer some insight into how key members of the Supreme Court are likely to analyze those issues.
Whether they succeed is likely to determine whether they have any chance of confirming anyone to the Supreme Court.